{"key":"processedPost-10145781","value":{"id":10145781,"first":10145482,"last":11151088,"when":1239427600,"utime":"04/11/09 08:26 AM","content":"No, use jars.&nbsp; The insulating effect of the glass acts as a buffer and keeps you from having extremes.&nbsp; As archivist said, just put your meat thermometer in the center of the jar and watch it carefully.&nbsp; Usually the water will boil for ten minutes or so before the temp in the jar begins to rise.&nbsp; Somewhere around 130F to 140F, shut off the stove.&nbsp; The temp will continue to rise, but shouldn't exceed 160F to 170F.&nbsp; Simply keep the temp in that range.&nbsp; If it starts to fall below 140F, turn the stove back on.&nbsp; You only have to babysit the process on the first time or two, and then you can just repeat what works with your jars, pot and stove each time.<br /><br />Don't jump the gun though.&nbsp; If growing pan cyans, you want to spawn to a thin manure layer first, and then when that is fully colonized, put your thin casing layer on.&nbsp; Pasteurize the manure as described above too.&nbsp; You can see it done by this method in the video on my website.&nbsp; Click on the manure prep page and watch the clip.<br />RR","title":"Re: Is Proper Pasteurization Easy to \"Screw Up\"?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}